  "prompt": "What are some examples of cardiac muscles?",
  "response": "Cardiac muscles, also known as myocardium, are found exclusively in the heart. They are specialized muscle tissues that facilitate the heart's ability to pump blood throughout the body. Here are some specific examples of cardiac muscles:\n\n1. **Atrial Muscle**: This type of cardiac muscle is found in the walls of the atria (the upper chambers of the heart). Atrial muscles are responsible for contracting to push blood into the ventricles.\n\n2. **Ventricular Muscle**: Located in the walls of the ventricles (the lower chambers of the heart), ventricular muscles are thicker and stronger than atrial muscles. They contract to pump blood out of the heart to the rest of the body and the lungs.\n\n3. **Papillary Muscles**: These are small muscles found within the ventricles. They are attached to the heart valves (the tricuspid and mitral valves) via chordae tendineae. Papillary muscles contract to prevent the inversion or prolapse of these valves during ventricular contraction.\n\n4. **Trabeculae Carneae**: These are raised columns of cardiac muscle fibers found on the inner surfaces of the ventricles. They help to enhance the contractile force of the heart and prevent the walls from adhering to each other.\n\n5. **Conduction System Muscles**: Specialized cardiac muscle cells form the heart's conduction system, which includes the sinoatrial (SA) node, atrioventricular (AV) node, bundle of His, and Purkinje fibers. These muscles generate and conduct electrical impulses that coordinate the heart's rhythmic contractions.\n\n6. **Septal Muscles**: The interventricular septum is the wall of muscle that separates the left and right ventricles. It contains cardiac muscle tissue that contracts synchronously with the ventricular walls to pump blood efficiently.\n\nThese examples highlight the specialized roles of cardiac muscles in maintaining the heart's function and ensuring effective circulation of blood throughout the body.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
